<h3 id="internet-data">Internet Data</h3>
<p><strong>Problem:</strong> Websites can see your location, and your Internet Service Provider can see your browsing history. Your computer has a unique number called an IP address, and every website can see that address. It allows them to find out roughly where your computer is. Using a different computer creates a different IP address (sort of).<br />
<strong>Solution 1:</strong> Using a VPN such as Nord or ProtonVPN can greatly improve the security of your browsing. While VPNs do require payment, they are usually very cheap. Never use a free VPN (except ProtonVPN), as they will make your browsing LESS secure by selling your data, adding adverts to your phone, or even infecting your phone with malware, which is how they make money. VPN stands for Virtual Private Network. It is a network of many different computers all over the world that act as intermediaries between your computer and the website you are visiting. This uses the IP address of the VPN computer instead of yours, meaning the website only sees the location of the VPN computer, not your computer. The connections between your computer and the cloud when you access a webpage is encrypted, meaning that while it is travelling to another computer owned by the VPN provider, nobody can read it. This means that with a no-logs vpn such as ProtonVPN or Nord, the browsing cannot easily be traced back to you without using other means. <br />
<strong>Solution 2:</strong> Another solution which is similar to using a VPN is to use Tor. Although Tor is infamous for being the gateway to the dark web, it is incredibly secure as your internet access is encrypted multiple times and sent all around the world. Do not ever use it for malicious purposes, as it is obviously illegal to interact with most dark websites. Furthermore, I would strongly advise against using it for secure activities, such as banking or personal unencrypted messaging, since the network is often under attack from both malicious users and governmant agencies.<br />
<strong>Keep yourself safe:</strong> Despite popular belief, using a VPN or Tor does not necessarily hide your identity. If you sign into a site that you have accessed without using the VPN even once, it is easily possible to connect the two. For example if you sign into your personal email account while using a VPN, although it is still encrypted, the website will immediately know that it is you using it since it will have a record of past login locations. So if you are concerned about websites finding out your identity, always use seperate accounts for encrypted and unencrypted connections. Also if you are browsing using a VPN or other service, especially Tor, you must always make sure the web address starts in â€śHTTPS://â€ť because browsing with only HTTP will destroy the benefit of having an encrypted connection, and allows hackers to easily get login or personal information. Another thing to note is that it is a good benefit to use two computers, one for using Tor or VPN on, and the other for any work that you do without a VPN, if any. Make sure that the one with the VPN or Tor on is a clean, fresh install of a common, up-to-date operating system such as Windows 10 or Ubuntu, and always change the size of the window each time you open a browsing tab and never browse in full-screen. I believe that Tor already changes the window size however. I would advise not to install any custom fonts or change any major system settings. If you are using Firefox, turn the anti-tracking settings to strict, as Firefox already has anti-fingerprinting methods built in. The extension NoScript Security Suite can also be helpful in reducing some fingerprinting or malicious JavaScript, however it could increase the likelyhood of fingerprinting unless you are using Tor which has NoScript built in.<br /></p>

